{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"[G4 child-consistency — container review of parent 1f19-adf2-ffb2-4b09 paired with THIS child (S2 70c7: Content-addressed snapshot cache + background janitor)]\n\nRan the 7 cross-child interaction modes for this cache/janitor child against the WHOLE sibling roster (S1 6d56 materialize core, S3 fa49 gate threading, S4 30b3 attested signing, S5 b7fa CLI/MCP surfacing, S6 1ba5 docs). All 7 modes are clean under the high-confidence / benign-reading filter. EMPTY G4 findings list for this pairing.\n\nMode-by-mode:\n\n1. Implicit shared state — CLEAN. This child OWNS the on-disk cache layout (`<cache>/<sha>/`, `tmp/`, `trash/`, `locks/<sha>`, `gc/lock`) and the running byte-total; it CONSUMES S1's atomic dir-rename primitive (\"populated via S1's atomic dir-rename\"). The producer/owner split at the cache root is mutually named and consistent: S1 builds into `<root>/tmp/<uuid>/` and renames into the cache path, and S1 AC3 states \"a crashed materialization leaves only a `tmp/` dir, cleaned on startup\"; THIS child's AC5 owns that cleanup (\"Startup sweep clears `tmp/*` and `trash/*` and reconciles the byte total via one full walk\"). S1 Scope \"Out: the cache/janitor (S2)\" ↔ S2 Scope \"Out: materialization itself (S1)\". No shared-state value is produced-without-consumer or consumed-without-producer; the tmp/ residue S1 leaves is precisely the residue this child sweeps. Consistent.\n\n2. Conflicting assumptions — CLEAN. This child is purely the ATTESTED-path cache; its text makes no local-mode claim, which is consistent with S3's \"Local: read the server's in-place checkout directly (no materialization, no cache)\" — local bypasses the cache entirely, so there is no contradicting assumption about whether local touches it. ADR ownership agrees across the roster: this child's AC13 owns the cache-architecture + rejected-PID+heartbeat-lease ADR, and S3 Scope explicitly defers to it (\"the architecture ADR (authored in S2, cross-referenced here)\"). S4's \"ADR 0002\" is the distinct pre-existing plan-review claim-gate ADR, not this child's cache ADR — no collision. The delete-on-last-close / kernel-guarantee posture (this child) and S1's faithful-snapshot content agree on a single immutable-SHA cache key (no staleness). No contradiction.\n\n3. Dependency gap — CLEAN. This child's reader-safety model REQUIRES a consumer-side complement: readers must \"open() files up front\" and \"treat ENOENT/EIO/short-read as miss → re-materialize\". That complement is owned by a named sibling — S3 AC6 (\"a gate tolerates an absent/being-GC'd snapshot dir by re-materializing (ENOENT → miss), never reading a partial tree\"). The atomic-population primitive this child depends on is produced by S1 (present, claims it). The configurable tunables this child introduces (watermark, grace window, max-age cutoff, reverify period) are documented by S6 (its disk-cap AC). No unowned upstream or downstream on this child's surface. (The standing S3↔S4 attest.py snapshot-handle routing seam is downstream of S1's resolved-SHA output and unrelated to this cache/janitor child.)\n\n4. Scope overlap — CLEAN. Two boundaries, both clean: (a) the atomic dir-rename population sits at the S1↔S2 boundary but is split cleanly — S1 OWNS the population primitive, this child CONSUMES it for cache-entry creation and adds eviction (rename-to-trash → rmtree) on top; no double-implementation (S1 Scope \"Out: the cache/janitor (S2)\"; S2 Scope \"Out: materialization itself (S1)\"). This child's \"single-flight per SHA\" (coalescing materialization for a given SHA) is a DISTINCT layer from S1's \"coalesced git fetch origin\" (coalescing the lock-taking fetch). (b) The portability flock seam is OWNED by S1 (fcntl.flock + atomic-mkdir fallback); this child's cross-process `flock(LOCK_EX)` on `locks/<sha>` and exclusive `flock` on `gc/lock` RIDE that seam without re-owning the tar/tmp/flock-fallback sub-clauses. No overlap.\n\n5. Ordering violation — CLEAN. S1 carries `blocks 70c7` (this child) — i.e. S1 → S2, coherent with the producer→consumer flow (the materialize core precedes the cache that populates from it). This child carries empty deps; parent AC8 only requires all-closed + green, so no encoded ordering is violated.\n\n6. Consumer impact — CLEAN. This child's delete-on-last-close contract (readers open fds up front; ENOENT/EIO/short-read → miss → re-materialize) imposes a reader obligation on its sole downstream consumer S3, which adopts exactly that in its AC6. The single-flight shared-entry semantics (second concurrent caller reads the shared entry) impose no redefinition on any sibling. No downstream contract is broken by this child's surface.\n\n7. Residual references — CLEAN. All cross-refs resolve: S1's atomic dir-rename (real producer in roster); the rejected PID+heartbeat lease (the spike outcome cited in the parent's Context/Design narrative); `shutil.disk_usage` (real stdlib); the configurable tunables → documented by S6 (its disk-cap/knobs AC). No dangling reference.\n\nNote: the cache/janitor module (src/rebar/_engine) does not yet exist in the tree (pre-manifest epic), so the analysis is grounded in the ticket-spec wording, not shipped code.\n\nNote (not a G4 finding on THIS pairing): the standing dependency-gap finding on sibling S4 (30b3) — routing the pinned-SHA snapshot handle into plan_review/attest.py's dependency_hashes()/_rehash()/claim-gate freshness re-check — is a code seam between S3 and S4; it does not touch this cache/janitor child and is out of this pairing's scope.\n\nConclusion: no high-confidence cross-child inconsistency between this cache/janitor child (S2) and the parent/siblings. Its content-addressed cache, single-flight, delete-on-last-close reader safety, free-space-watermark LRU reclamation, rename-to-trash eviction, gc/lock interlock, byte-total integrity, and ADR form clean producer/consumer splits with S1 (population → cache), S3 (delete-on-last-close → ENOENT-miss tolerance), and S6 (tunables → docs). Empty G4 findings list for this pairing."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782527563534486001,"uuid":"0781cccf-a79a-411b-aa95-c1bed48e31aa"}